	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />- When I wrote my CPU core, I used a single reference that 1 CPU clock equals to 3 PPU clocks. By reading the CPU opcodes reference, it seems clear enough that if a certain instruction (example) uses 1 cycle to fetch the opcode, another for the immediate byte and another for reading memory, so the PPU would execute 3 cycles per CPU cycle. By the way, the last CPU test ROMs <strong>fail</strong> and nobody could make my question answered... I knew the "half" CPU cycle thing, but what about the PPU itself? An hypotetical example (sorry for those ones that <em>dislike</em> pasting any code):
<br />
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">//this is pseudo-code<br /><br />opcode = readmem&#40;cpu-&gt;PC&#41;; ppu_clock&#40;3&#41;;<br />byte = readmem&#40;cpu-&gt;PC&#41;; ppu_clock&#40;3&#41;;<br />cpu-&gt;A = readmem&#40;byte&#41;;<br />ppu_clock&#40;3&#41;; //executes 3 PPU cycles</div>
<br />
<br />The following block gives me an error of +1 CPU cycle. I wonder why...

		

		</td>
	</tr>
